# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mpemba-effect
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] The ***American Journal of Physics*** is a monthly, peer-reviewed scientific journal published by the American Association of Physics Teachers and the American Institute of Physics.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] The editor-in-chief is Beth Parks of Colgate University.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] The focus of this journal is undergraduate and graduate level physics.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] The intended audience is college and university physics teachers and students.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] Coverage includes current research in physics, instructional laboratory equipment, laboratory demonstrations, teaching methodologies, lists of resources, and book reviews.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] In addition, historical, philosophical and cultural aspects of physics are also covered.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] According to the 2021 Journal Citation Reports from Clarivate, this journal has a 2020 impact factor of 1.022.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] The former title of this journal was *American Physics Teacher* (vol.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] It was a quarterly journal from 1933 to 1936, and then a bimonthly from 1937 to 1939.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] After volume 7 was published in December 1939, the name of the journal was changed to its current title in February 1940.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] Hence, the publication begins under its new title with volume 8 in February 1940.
[src:mpemba-effect/american-journal-of-physics] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2023 impact factor of 0.8.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Markov and his younger brother Vladimir Andreyevich Markov (1871–1897) proved the Markov brothers' inequality.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] His son, another Andrey Andreyevich Markov (1903–1979), was also a notable mathematician, making contributions to constructive mathematics and recursive function theory.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Andrey Markov was born on 14 June 1856 in Ryazan, Russia.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Petersburg Grammar School, where some teachers saw him as a rebellious student.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] In his academics he performed poorly in most subjects other than mathematics.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Later in life he attended Saint Petersburg Imperial University.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] He completed his studies at the university and was later asked if he would like to stay and have a career as a mathematician.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] He later taught at high schools and continued his own mathematical studies.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] In this time he found a practical use for his mathematical skills.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] In 1913, he conducted a study on the distribution of vowels and consonants in the first 20,000 letters of Alexander Pushkin's *Eugene Onegin*, treating the text as a sequence of symbols and analyzing the statistical relationships between them.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] By classifying each letter as either a vowel or a consonant and analyzing the probabilities of transitions between these categories, Markov demonstrated that chains of dependent events could be rigorously modeled.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] This was the first empirical application of what are now called Markov chains.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] During the following year, he passed the candidate's examinations, and he remained at the university to prepare for a lecturer's position.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] In April 1880, Markov defended his master's thesis "On the Binary Square Forms with Positive Determinant", which was directed by Aleksandr Korkin and Yegor Zolotarev.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Four years later in 1884, he defended his doctoral thesis titled "On Certain Applications of the Algebraic Continuous Fractions".
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] His pedagogical work began after the defense of his master's thesis in autumn 1880.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] As a privatdozent he lectured on differential and integral calculus.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Later he lectured alternately on "introduction to analysis", probability theory (succeeding Chebyshev, who had left the university in 1882) and the calculus of differences.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] From 1895 through 1905 he also lectured in differential calculus.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] One year after the defense of his doctoral thesis, Markov was appointed extraordinary professor (1886) and in the same year he was elected adjunct to the Academy of Sciences.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] In 1890, after the death of Viktor Bunyakovsky, Markov became an extraordinary member of the academy.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] His promotion to an ordinary professor of St.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Petersburg University followed in the fall of 1894.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] In 1896, Markov was elected an ordinary member of the academy as the successor of Chebyshev.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] In 1905, he was appointed merited professor and was granted the right to retire, which he did immediately.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Until 1910, however, he continued to lecture in the calculus of differences.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] In connection with student riots in 1908, professors and lecturers of St.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Petersburg University were ordered to monitor their students.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Markov refused to accept this decree, and he wrote an explanation in which he declined to be an "agent of the governance".
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Markov was removed from further teaching duties at St.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Petersburg University, and hence he decided to retire from the university.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] In 1912, he responded to Leo Tolstoy's excommunication from the Russian Orthodox Church by requesting his own excommunication.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Petersburg elected nine scientists honorary members of the university.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Markov was among them, but his election was not affirmed by the minister of education.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] The affirmation only occurred four years later, after the February Revolution in 1917.
[src:mpemba-effect/andrey-markov] Markov then resumed his teaching activities and lectured on probability theory and the calculus of differences until his death in 1922.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Generally, antiferromagnetic order may exist at sufficiently low temperatures, but vanishes at and above the Néel temperature – named after Louis Néel, who had first identified this type of magnetic ordering.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Above the Néel temperature, the material is typically paramagnetic.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] When no external field is applied, the antiferromagnetic structure corresponds to a vanishing total magnetization.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] In an external magnetic field, a kind of ferrimagnetic behavior may be displayed in the antiferromagnetic phase, with the absolute value of one of the sublattice magnetizations differing from that of the other sublattice, resulting in a nonzero net magnetization.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Although the net magnetization should be zero at a temperature of absolute zero, the effect of spin canting often causes a small net magnetization to develop, as seen for example in hematite.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] The magnetic susceptibility of an antiferromagnetic material typically shows a maximum at the Néel temperature.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] In contrast, at the transition between the ferromagnetic to the paramagnetic phases the susceptibility will diverge.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] In the antiferromagnetic case, a divergence is observed in the *staggered susceptibility*.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Various microscopic (exchange) interactions between the magnetic moments or spins may lead to antiferromagnetic structures.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] In the simplest case, one may consider an Ising model on a bipartite lattice, e.g. the simple cubic lattice, with couplings between spins at nearest neighbor sites.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Depending on the sign of that interaction, ferromagnetic or antiferromagnetic order will result.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Geometrical frustration or competing ferro- and antiferromagnetic interactions may lead to different and, perhaps, more complicated magnetic structures.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] The relationship between magnetization and the magnetizing field is non-linear like in ferromagnetic materials.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] This fact is due to the contribution of the hysteresis loop, which for ferromagnetic materials involves a residual magnetization.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Antiferromagnetic structures were first shown through neutron diffraction of transition metal oxides such as nickel, iron, and manganese oxides.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] The experiments, performed by Clifford Shull, gave the first results showing that magnetic dipoles could be oriented in an antiferromagnetic structure.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Antiferromagnetic materials occur commonly among transition metal compounds, especially oxides.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Examples include hematite, metals such as chromium, alloys such as iron manganese (FeMn), and oxides such as nickel oxide (NiO).
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] There are also numerous examples among high nuclearity metal clusters.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Organic molecules can also exhibit antiferromagnetic coupling under rare circumstances, as seen in radicals such as 5-dehydro-m-xylylene.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] This provides the ability to "pin" the orientation of a ferromagnetic film, which provides one of the main uses in so-called spin valves, which are the basis of magnetic sensors including modern hard disk drive read heads.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] The temperature at or above which an antiferromagnetic layer loses its ability to "pin" the magnetization direction of an adjacent ferromagnetic layer is called the blocking temperature of that layer and is usually lower than the Néel temperature.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Unlike ferromagnetism, anti-ferromagnetic interactions can lead to multiple optimal states (ground states—states of minimal energy).
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] In one dimension, the anti-ferromagnetic ground state is an alternating series of spins: up, down, up, down, etc.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Yet in two dimensions, multiple ground states can occur.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Consider an equilateral triangle with three spins, one on each vertex.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] If each spin can take on only two values (up or down), there are 23 = 8 possible states of the system, six of which are ground states.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] The two situations which are not ground states are when all three spins are up or are all down.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] In any of the other six states, there will be two favorable interactions and one unfavorable one.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] This illustrates frustration: the inability of the system to find a single ground state.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] This type of magnetic behavior has been found in minerals that have a crystal stacking structure such as a Kagome lattice or hexagonal lattice.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Synthetic antiferromagnets (often abbreviated by SAF) are artificial antiferromagnets consisting of two or more thin ferromagnetic layers separated by a nonmagnetic layer.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Dipole coupling of the ferromagnetic layers results in antiparallel alignment of the magnetization of the ferromagnets.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] Antiferromagnetism plays a crucial role in devices employing giant magnetoresistance (GMR), an effect discovered in 1988 by the Nobel Prize winners Albert Fert and Peter Grünberg (awarded in 2007).
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] First, for antiferromagnets being employed as pinning layers and also since the original device design (iron-chromium-iron multilayer with the Cr layer thickness carefully tuned) amounts to a synthetic antiferromagnet.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] There are also examples of disordered materials (such as iron phosphate glasses) that become antiferromagnetic below their Néel temperature.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] These disordered networks 'frustrate' the antiparallelism of adjacent spins; i.e. it is not possible to construct a network where each spin is surrounded by opposite neighbour spins.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] It can only be determined that the average correlation of neighbour spins is antiferromagnetic.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiferromagnetism] This type of magnetism is sometimes called speromagnetism.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In modern physics, **antimatter** is defined as matter composed of the antiparticles (or "partners") of the corresponding particles in "ordinary" matter, and can be thought of as matter with reversed charges and parity, or going backward in time (see CPT symmetry).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antimatter occurs in natural processes like cosmic ray collisions and some types of radioactive decay.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antiparticles can also be generated at particle accelerators, but only a tiny fraction of these have successfully been bound together in experiments to form antiatoms.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Total artificial production has been only a few nanograms.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] No macroscopic amount of antimatter has ever been assembled due to the extreme cost and difficulty of production and handling.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Nonetheless, antimatter is an essential component of widely available applications related to beta decay, such as positron emission tomography, radiation therapy, and industrial imaging.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In theory, a particle and its antiparticle (for example, a proton and an antiproton) have the same mass, but opposite electric charge, and other differences in quantum numbers.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] A collision between any particle and its anti-particle partner leads to their mutual annihilation, giving rise to different proportions of intense photons (gamma rays), neutrinos, and sometimes less-massive particle–antiparticle pairs.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The majority of the total energy of annihilation emerges in the form of ionizing radiation.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] If surrounding matter is present, the energy content of this radiation will be absorbed and converted into other forms of energy, such as heat or light.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The amount of energy released is usually proportional to the total mass of the collided matter and antimatter, in accordance with the mass–energy equivalence equation, *E*=*mc*2.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antiparticles bind with each other to form antimatter, just as ordinary particles bind to form normal matter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] For example, a positron (the antiparticle of the electron) and an antiproton (the antiparticle of the proton) can form an antihydrogen atom.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The nuclei of antihelium have been artificially produced, albeit with difficulty, and are the most complex anti-nuclei so far observed.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Physical principles indicate that complex antimatter atomic nuclei are possible, as well as anti-atoms corresponding to the known chemical elements.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] There is strong evidence that the observable universe is composed almost entirely of ordinary matter, as opposed to an equal mixture of matter and antimatter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This asymmetry of matter and antimatter in the visible universe is one of the great unsolved problems in physics.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The process by which this inequality between matter and antimatter particles is hypothesised to have occurred is called baryogenesis.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antimatter particles carry the same charge as matter particles, but of opposite sign.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] That is, an antiproton is negatively charged and an antielectron (positron) is positively charged.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Neutrons do not carry a net charge, but their constituent quarks do.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Protons and neutrons have a baryon number of +1, while antiprotons and antineutrons have a baryon number of –1.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Similarly, electrons have a lepton number of +1, while that of positrons is –1.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] When a particle and its corresponding antiparticle collide, they are both converted into energy.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The French term for "made of or pertaining to antimatter", *contraterrene*, led to the initialism "C.T." and the science fiction term *seetee*, as used in such novels as *Seetee Ship*.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The idea of negative matter appears in past theories of matter that have now been abandoned.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Using the once popular vortex theory of gravity, the possibility of matter with negative gravity was discussed by William Hicks in the 1880s.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Between the 1880s and the 1890s, Karl Pearson proposed the existence of "squirts" and sinks of the flow of aether.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The squirts represented normal matter and the sinks represented negative matter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Pearson's theory required a fourth dimension for the aether to flow from and into.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The term antimatter was first used by Arthur Schuster in two rather whimsical letters to *Nature* in 1898, in which he coined the term.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] He hypothesized antiatoms, as well as whole antimatter solar systems, and discussed the possibility of matter and antimatter annihilating each other.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Schuster's ideas were not a serious theoretical proposal, merely speculation, and like the previous ideas, differed from the modern concept of antimatter in that it possessed negative gravity.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The modern theory of antimatter began in 1928, with a paper by Paul Dirac.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Dirac realised that his relativistic version of the Schrödinger wave equation for electrons predicted the possibility of antielectrons.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Although Dirac had laid the groundwork for the existence of these "antielectrons" he initially failed to pick up on the implications contained within his own equation.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] He freely gave the credit for that insight to J.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Robert Oppenheimer, whose seminal paper "On the Theory of Electrons and Protons" (Feb 14th 1930) drew on Dirac's equation and argued for the existence of a positively charged electron (a positron), which as a counterpart to the electron should have the same mass as the electron itself.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This meant that it could not be, as Dirac had in fact suggested, a proton.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Dirac further postulated the existence of antimatter in a 1931 paper which referred to the positron as an "anti-electron".
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Anderson in 1932 and named positrons from "positive electron".
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Although Dirac did not himself use the term antimatter, its use follows on naturally enough from antielectrons, antiprotons, etc.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The Feynman–Stueckelberg interpretation states that antiparticles obey the same equations of motion as regular particles but with charge, parity and time inverted.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This allows analysis of antiparticles using Feynman diagrams with time reversed.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] After Carl Anderson's discovery of the positron in 1932, it was 22 years before the next antimatter particle was found.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In 1955 Chamberlain, Segrè, Wiegand, Ypsilantis publish their the discovery of the antiproton and in 1956 Cork, Lambertson, Piccioni, Wenzel discovered the antineutron.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Both teams used the Bevatron in Berkeley, California.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The discovery of antimatter led to both scientific and science fiction speculations on astronomical antimatter bodies: **antiplanets**, antistars, and **antigalaxies**.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Leon Lederman at Columbia University even speculated anti-planets might harbor intelligent life.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The antigalaxy idea was also used to explain the baryon asymmetry problem: the particle physics of the Big Bang model cannot explain why our universe has more matter than antimatter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Maurice Goldhaber suggested that our universe consists of matter rather than antimatter because the one universe of each type split at the beginning of time.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] By the 1970s the asymmetry problem was accepted as unexplained and the possibility of antigalaxies largely abandoned.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] One way to denote an antiparticle is by adding a bar over the particle's symbol.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] For example, the proton and antiproton are denoted as p and p, respectively.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The same rule applies if one were to address a particle by its constituent components.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] A proton is made up of u u d quarks, so an antiproton must therefore be formed from u u d antiquarks.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Another convention is to distinguish particles by positive and negative electric charge.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Thus, the electron and positron are denoted simply as e− and e+ respectively.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] To prevent confusion, however, the two conventions are never mixed.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] There is no difference in the gravitational behavior of matter and antimatter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In other words, antimatter falls down when dropped, not up.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This was confirmed with the thin, very cold gas of thousands of antihydrogen atoms that were confined in a vertical shaft surrounded by superconducting electromagnetic coils.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] These can create a magnetic bottle to keep the antimatter from coming into contact with matter and annihilating.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The researchers then gradually weakened the magnetic fields and detected the antiatoms using two sensors as they escaped and annihilated.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Most of the anti-atoms came out of the bottom opening, and only one-quarter out of the top.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] There are compelling theoretical reasons to believe that, aside from the fact that antiparticles have different signs on all charges (such as electric and baryon charges), matter and antimatter have exactly the same properties.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This means a particle and its corresponding antiparticle must have identical masses and decay lifetimes (if unstable).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] It also implies that, for example, a star made up of antimatter (an "antistar") will shine just like an ordinary star.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This idea was tested experimentally in 2016 by the ALPHA experiment, which measured the transition between the two lowest energy states of antihydrogen.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The results, which are identical to that of hydrogen, confirmed the validity of quantum mechanics for antimatter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Most things observable from the Earth seem to be made of matter rather than antimatter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] If antimatter-dominated regions of space existed, the gamma rays produced in annihilation reactions along the boundary between matter and antimatter regions would be detectable.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antiparticles are created everywhere in the universe where high-energy particle collisions take place.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] High-energy cosmic rays striking Earth's atmosphere (or any other matter in the Solar System) produce minute quantities of antiparticles in the resulting particle jets, which are immediately annihilated by contact with nearby matter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] They may similarly be produced in regions like the center of the Milky Way and other galaxies, where very energetic celestial events occur (principally the interaction of relativistic jets with the interstellar medium).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The presence of the resulting antimatter is detectable by the two gamma rays produced every time positrons annihilate with nearby matter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The frequency and wavelength of the gamma rays indicate that each carries 511 keV of energy (that is, the rest mass of an electron multiplied by *c*2).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Observations by the European Space Agency's INTEGRAL satellite may explain the origin of a giant antimatter cloud surrounding the Galactic Center.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The observations show that the cloud is asymmetrical and matches the pattern of X-ray binaries (binary star systems containing black holes or neutron stars), mostly on one side of the Galactic Center.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] While the mechanism is not fully understood, it is likely to involve the production of electron–positron pairs, as ordinary matter gains kinetic energy while falling into a stellar remnant.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antimatter may exist in relatively large amounts in far-away galaxies due to cosmic inflation in the primordial time of the universe.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antimatter galaxies, if they exist, are expected to have the same chemistry and absorption and emission spectra as normal-matter galaxies, and their astronomical objects would be observationally identical, making them difficult to distinguish.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] NASA is trying to determine if such galaxies exist by looking for X-ray and gamma ray signatures of annihilation events in colliding superclusters.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In October 2017, scientists working on the BASE experiment at CERN reported a measurement of the antiproton magnetic moment to a precision of 1.5 parts per billion.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] It is consistent with the most precise measurement of the proton magnetic moment (also made by BASE in 2014), which supports the hypothesis of CPT symmetry.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This measurement represents the first time that a property of antimatter is known more precisely than the equivalent property in matter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antimatter quantum interferometry has been first demonstrated in 2018 in the Positron Laboratory (L-NESS) of Rafael Ferragut in Como (Italy), by a group led by Marco Giammarchi.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Positrons are produced naturally in β+ decays of naturally occurring radioactive isotopes (for example, potassium-40) and in interactions of gamma quanta (emitted by radioactive nuclei) with matter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antineutrinos are another kind of antiparticle created by natural radioactivity (β− decay).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Many different kinds of antiparticles are also produced by (and contained in) cosmic rays.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In January 2011, research by the American Astronomical Society discovered antimatter (positrons) originating above thunderstorm clouds; positrons are produced in terrestrial gamma ray flashes created by electrons accelerated by strong electric fields in the clouds.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antiprotons have also been found to exist in the Van Allen Belts around the Earth by the PAMELA module, and similar antiproton belts may exist around Jupiter, Saturn, Neptune, and Uranus.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antiparticles are also produced in any environment with a sufficiently high temperature (mean particle energy greater than the pair production threshold).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] It is hypothesized that during the period of baryogenesis, when the universe was extremely hot and dense, matter and antimatter were continually produced and annihilated.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The presence of remaining matter, and absence of detectable remaining antimatter, is called baryon asymmetry.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The exact mechanism that produced this asymmetry during baryogenesis remains an unsolved problem.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] One of the necessary conditions for this asymmetry is the violation of CP symmetry, which has been experimentally observed in the weak interaction.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Recent observations indicate black holes and neutron stars produce vast amounts of positron-electron plasma via the jets.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Satellite experiments have found evidence of positrons and a few antiprotons in primary cosmic rays, amounting to less than 1% of the particles in primary cosmic rays.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This antimatter cannot all have been created in the Big Bang, but is instead attributed to have been produced by cyclic processes at high energies.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] For instance, electron-positron pairs may be formed in pulsars, as a magnetized neutron star rotation cycle shears electron-positron pairs from the star surface.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Therein the antimatter forms a wind that crashes upon the ejecta of the progenitor supernovae.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Preliminary results from the presently operating Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer (*AMS-02*) on board the International Space Station show that positrons in the cosmic rays arrive with no directionality, and with energies that range from 10 GeV to 250 GeV.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In September, 2014, new results with almost twice as much data were presented in a talk at CERN and published in Physical Review Letters.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] A new measurement of positron fraction up to 500 GeV was reported, showing that positron fraction peaks at a maximum of about 16% of total electron+positron events, around an energy of 275 ± 32 GeV.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] At higher energies, up to 500 GeV, the ratio of positrons to electrons begins to fall again.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The absolute flux of positrons also begins to fall before 500 GeV, but peaks at energies far higher than electron energies, which peak about 10 GeV.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] These results on interpretation have been suggested to be due to positron production in annihilation events of massive dark matter particles.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Cosmic ray antiprotons also have a much higher energy than their normal-matter counterparts (protons).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] They arrive at Earth with a characteristic energy maximum of 2 GeV, indicating their production in a fundamentally different process from cosmic ray protons, which on average have only one-sixth of the energy.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] There is an ongoing search for larger antimatter nuclei, such as antihelium nuclei (that is, anti-alpha particles), in cosmic rays.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The detection of natural antihelium could imply the existence of large antimatter structures such as an antistar.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] A prototype of the *AMS-02* designated *AMS-01*, was flown into space aboard the Space Shuttle *Discovery* on STS-91 in June 1998.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] By not detecting any antihelium at all, the *AMS-01* established an upper limit of 1.1×10−6 for the antihelium to helium flux ratio.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] AMS-02 revealed in December 2016 that it had discovered a few signals consistent with antihelium nuclei amidst several billion helium nuclei.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The result remains to be verified, and as of 2017, the team is trying to rule out contamination.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Positrons were reported in November 2008 to have been generated by Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in large numbers.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] A laser drove electrons through a gold target's nuclei, which caused the incoming electrons to emit energy quanta that decayed into both matter and antimatter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Positrons were detected at a higher rate and in greater density than ever previously detected in a laboratory.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Previous experiments made smaller quantities of positrons using lasers and paper-thin targets; newer simulations showed that short bursts of ultra-intense lasers and millimeter-thick gold are a far more effective source.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In 2023, the production of the first electron-positron beam-plasma was reported by a collaboration led by researchers at University of Oxford working with the High-Radiation to Materials (HRMT) facility at CERN.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The beam demonstrated the highest positron yield achieved so far in a laboratory setting.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The experiment employed the 440 GeV proton beam, with $3\times 10^{11}$ protons, from the Super Proton Synchrotron, and irradiated a particle converter composed of carbon and tantalum.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This yielded a total $1.5\times 10^{13}$ electron-positron pairs via a particle shower process.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The produced pair beams have a volume that fills multiple Debye spheres and are thus able to sustain collective plasma oscillations.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The existence of the antiproton was experimentally confirmed in 1955 by University of California, Berkeley physicists Emilio Segrè and Owen Chamberlain, for which they were awarded the 1959 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] An antiproton consists of two up antiquarks and one down antiquark (uud).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The properties of the antiproton that have been measured all match the corresponding properties of the proton, with the exception of the antiproton having opposite electric charge and magnetic moment from the proton.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Shortly afterwards, in 1956, the antineutron was discovered in proton–proton collisions at the Bevatron (Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory) by Bruce Cork and colleagues.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In addition to antibaryons, anti-nuclei consisting of multiple bound antiprotons and antineutrons have been created.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] These are typically produced at energies far too high to form antimatter atoms (with bound positrons in place of electrons).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In 1965, a group of researchers led by Antonino Zichichi reported production of nuclei of antideuterium at the Proton Synchrotron at CERN.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] At roughly the same time, observations of antideuterium nuclei were reported by a group of American physicists at the Alternating Gradient Synchrotron at Brookhaven National Laboratory.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In 1995, CERN announced that it had successfully brought into existence nine hot antihydrogen atoms by implementing the SLAC/Fermilab concept during the PS210 experiment.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The experiment was performed using the Low Energy Antiproton Ring (LEAR), and was led by Walter Oelert and Mario Macri.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Fermilab soon confirmed the CERN findings by producing approximately 100 antihydrogen atoms at their facilities.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The antihydrogen atoms created during PS210 and subsequent experiments (at both CERN and Fermilab) were extremely energetic and were not well suited to study.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] To resolve this hurdle, and to gain a better understanding of antihydrogen, two collaborations were formed in the late 1990s, namely, ATHENA and ATRAP.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In 1999, CERN activated the Antiproton Decelerator, a device capable of decelerating antiprotons from 3.5 GeV to 5.3 MeV – still too "hot" to produce study-effective antihydrogen, but a huge leap forward.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In late 2002 the ATHENA project announced that they had created the world's first "cold" antihydrogen.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The ATRAP project released similar results very shortly thereafter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The antiprotons used in these experiments were cooled by decelerating them with the Antiproton Decelerator, passing them through a thin sheet of foil, and finally capturing them in a Penning–Malmberg trap.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The overall cooling process is workable, but highly inefficient; approximately 25 million antiprotons leave the Antiproton Decelerator and roughly 25,000 make it to the Penning–Malmberg trap, which is about ⁠1/1000⁠ or 0.1% of the original amount.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The antiprotons are still hot when initially trapped.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] To cool them further, they are mixed into an electron plasma.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The electrons in this plasma cool via cyclotron radiation, and then sympathetically cool the antiprotons via Coulomb collisions.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Eventually, the electrons are removed by the application of short-duration electric fields, leaving the antiprotons with energies less than 100 meV.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] While the antiprotons are being cooled in the first trap, a small cloud of positrons is captured from radioactive sodium in a Surko-style positron accumulator.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This cloud is then recaptured in a second trap near the antiprotons.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Manipulations of the trap electrodes then tip the antiprotons into the positron plasma, where some combine with antiprotons to form antihydrogen.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This neutral antihydrogen is unaffected by the electric and magnetic fields used to trap the charged positrons and antiprotons, and within a few microseconds the antihydrogen hits the trap walls, where it annihilates.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Some hundreds of millions of antihydrogen atoms have been made in this fashion.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In 2005, ATHENA disbanded and some of the former members (along with others) formed the ALPHA Collaboration, which is also based at CERN.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The ultimate goal of this endeavour is to test CPT symmetry through comparison of the atomic spectra of hydrogen and antihydrogen (see hydrogen spectral series).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Most of the sought-after high-precision tests of the properties of antihydrogen could only be performed if the antihydrogen were trapped, that is, held in place for a relatively long time.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] While antihydrogen atoms are electrically neutral, the spins of their component particles produce a magnetic moment.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] These magnetic moments can interact with an inhomogeneous magnetic field; some of the antihydrogen atoms can be attracted to a magnetic minimum.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Such a minimum can be created by a combination of mirror and multipole fields.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antihydrogen can be trapped in such a magnetic minimum (minimum-B) trap; in November 2010, the ALPHA collaboration announced that they had so trapped 38 antihydrogen atoms for about a sixth of a second.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This was the first time that neutral antimatter had been trapped.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] On 26 April 2011, ALPHA announced that they had trapped 309 antihydrogen atoms, some for as long as 1,000 seconds (about 17 minutes).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This was longer than neutral antimatter had ever been trapped before.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] ALPHA has used these trapped atoms to initiate research into the spectral properties of antihydrogen.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In 2016, a new antiproton decelerator and cooler called ELENA (extra low energy antiproton decelerator) was built.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] It takes the antiprotons from the antiproton decelerator and cools them to 90 keV, which is "cold" enough to study.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This machine works by using high energy and accelerating the particles within the chamber.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] More than one hundred antiprotons can be captured per second, a huge improvement, but it would still take several thousand years to make a nanogram of antimatter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The biggest limiting factor in the large-scale production of antimatter is the availability of antiprotons.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Recent data released by CERN states that, when fully operational, their facilities are capable of producing ten million antiprotons per minute.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Assuming a 100% conversion of antiprotons to antihydrogen, it would take 100 billion years to produce 1 gram or 1 mole of antihydrogen (approximately 6.02×1023 atoms of antihydrogen).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] However, CERN only produces 1% of the antimatter Fermilab does, and neither are designed to produce antimatter.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] According to Gerald Jackson, using technology already in use today we are capable of producing and capturing 20 grams of antimatter particles per year at a yearly cost of 670 million dollars per facility.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antihelium-3 nuclei (3 He, i.e. two antiprotons and one antineutron) were first observed in the 1970s in proton–nucleus collision experiments at the Institute for High Energy Physics by Y.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Prockoshkin's group (Protvino near Moscow, USSR) and later created in nucleus–nucleus collision experiments.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Nucleus–nucleus collisions produce antinuclei through the coalescence of antiprotons and antineutrons created in these reactions.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In 2011, the STAR detector reported the observation of artificially created antihelium-4 nuclei (anti-alpha particles) (4 He) from such collisions.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer on the International Space Station has, as of 2021, recorded eight events that seem to indicate the detection of antihelium-3.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antimatter cannot be stored in a container made of ordinary matter because antimatter reacts with any matter it touches, annihilating itself and an equal amount of the container.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antimatter in the form of charged particles can be contained by a combination of electric and magnetic fields, in a device called a Penning trap.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This device cannot, however, contain antimatter that consists of uncharged particles, for which atomic traps are used.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In particular, such a trap may use the dipole moment (electric or magnetic) of the trapped particles.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] At high vacuum, the matter or antimatter particles can be trapped and cooled with slightly off-resonant laser radiation using a magneto-optical trap or magnetic trap.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Small particles can also be suspended with optical tweezers, using a highly focused laser beam.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The record for storing antiparticles is currently held by the TRAP experiment at CERN: antiprotons were kept in a Penning trap for 405 days.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] CERN scientists have demonstrated the transportation of 92 antiprotons for a distance of about five miles using BASE-STEP, a 1,000 kg (2,200 lb) truck-mounted cryogenic Penning trap apparatus, paving the way for practical shipments of antimatter to other institutions for study.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Scientists claim that antimatter is the costliest material to make.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In 2006, Gerald Smith estimated $250 million could produce 10 milligrams of positrons (equivalent to $25 billion per gram); in 1999, NASA gave a figure of $62.5 trillion per gram of antihydrogen.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] This is because production is difficult (only very few antiprotons are produced in reactions in particle accelerators) and because there is higher demand for other uses of particle accelerators.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] According to CERN, it has cost a few hundred million Swiss francs to produce about 1 billionth of a gram (the amount used so far for particle/antiparticle collisions).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In comparison, to produce the first atomic weapon, the cost of the Manhattan Project was estimated at $23 billion with inflation during 2007.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Several studies funded by NASA Innovative Advanced Concepts are exploring whether it might be possible to use magnetic scoops to collect the antimatter that occurs naturally in the Van Allen belt of the Earth, and ultimately the belts of gas giants like Jupiter, ideally at a lower cost per gram.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Matter–antimatter reactions have practical applications in medical imaging, such as positron emission tomography (PET).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In positive beta decay, a nuclide loses surplus positive charge by emitting a positron (in the same event, a proton becomes a neutron, and a neutrino is also emitted).
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Nuclides with surplus positive charge are easily made in a cyclotron and are widely generated for medical use.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antiprotons have also been shown within laboratory experiments to have the potential to treat certain cancers, in a similar method currently used for ion (proton) therapy.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Isolated and stored antimatter could be used as a fuel for interplanetary or interstellar travel as part of an antimatter-catalyzed nuclear pulse propulsion or another antimatter rocket.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Since the energy density of antimatter is higher than that of conventional fuels, an antimatter-fueled spacecraft would have a higher thrust-to-weight ratio than a conventional spacecraft.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] If matter–antimatter collisions resulted only in photon emission, the entire rest mass of the particles would be converted to kinetic energy.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Not all of that energy can be utilized by any realistic propulsion technology because of the nature of the annihilation products.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] While electron–positron reactions result in gamma ray photons, these are difficult to direct and use for thrust.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] In reactions between protons and antiprotons, their energy is converted largely into relativistic neutral and charged pions.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] The neutral pions decay almost immediately (with a lifetime of 85 attoseconds) into high-energy photons, but the charged pions decay more slowly (with a lifetime of 26 nanoseconds) and can be deflected magnetically to produce thrust.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Antimatter has been considered as a trigger mechanism for nuclear weapons.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] A major obstacle is the difficulty of producing antimatter in large enough quantities, and there is no evidence that it will ever be feasible.
[src:mpemba-effect/antimatter] Air Force funded studies of the physics of antimatter in the Cold War, and began considering its possible use in weapons, not just as a trigger, but as the explosive itself.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] Historically, antiperistasis as a type of explanation was applied to numerous phenomena, from the interaction of quicklime with cold water, to the origin of thunder and lightning.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] In his *Timaeus*, Plato introduces the concept of *periosis* pushing around in order to explain various phenomena.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] Plato, for instance, appeals to it to explain how respiration functions in human beings.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] His 'theory' has been most famously adopted by Aristotle who made popular the term antiperistasis.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] In a nutshell it was "the doctrine that a moving object, which is no longer in touch with the mover, is moved by the medium through which it moves.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] Logically, it is connected to the idea that void does not exist.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] It was using this explanation that academic philosophers claimed that cold, on many occasions, increases a body's temperature, and dryness increases its moisture.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] Thus, it was said, quicklime (CaO) was apparently set ablaze when doused with cold water (an effect later explained as an exothermic reaction).
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] It was also the understood reason for why water, such as that in wells, appeared warmer in winter than in summer (later explained as an example of sensory adaptation).
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] It was also suggested that thunder and lightning were the results of antiperistasis caused by the coldness of the sky.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] Peripatetic philosophers, who were followers of Aristotle, made extensive use of the principle of antiperistasis.
[src:mpemba-effect/antiperistasis] Other examples used by the proponents of antiperistasis included the aphoristical saying of Hippocrates, "the viscera are hottest in the winter"; and the production of hail in the upper atmosphere, believed to occur only in the summer due to the increased heat of the sun.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He was born in the city of Stagira in Chalkidiki (northern Greece) during the Classical period.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] His father, Nicomachus, died when Aristotle was a child, and he was brought up by a guardian.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] At around eighteen years old, he joined Plato's Academy in Athens and remained there until the age of thirty seven (c.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Shortly after Plato died, Aristotle left Athens and, at the request of Philip II of Macedon, tutored his son Alexander the Great beginning in 343 BC.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He established a library in the Lyceum, which helped him to produce many of his hundreds of books on papyrus scrolls.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Though Aristotle wrote many treatises and dialogues for publication, only around a third of his original output has survived, none of it intended for publication.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle provided a complex synthesis of the various philosophies existing prior to him.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] His teachings and methods of inquiry have had a significant impact across the world, and remain a subject of contemporary philosophical discussion.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's views profoundly shaped medieval scholarship.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The influence of his physical science extended from late antiquity and the Early Middle Ages into the Renaissance, and was not replaced systematically until the Enlightenment and theories such as classical mechanics were developed.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He influenced Judeo-Islamic philosophies during the Middle Ages, as well as Christian theology, especially the Neoplatonism of the Early Church and the scholastic tradition of the Catholic Church.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle was revered among medieval Muslim scholars as "The First Teacher", and among medieval Christians like Thomas Aquinas as simply "The Philosopher".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He has been referred to as the first scientist.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] His works contain the earliest known systematic study of logic, and were studied by medieval scholars such as Peter Abelard and Jean Buridan.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] His influence on logic continued well into the 19th century.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In addition, his ethics, although always influential, has gained renewed interest with the modern advent of virtue ethics.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In general, the details of Aristotle's life are not well-established.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The biographies written in ancient times are often speculative and historians only agree on a few salient points.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle was born in 384 BC in Stagira, Chalcidice, about 55 km (34 miles) east of modern-day Thessaloniki.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He was the son of Nicomachus, the personal physician of King Amyntas of Macedon, and Phaestis, a woman with origins from Chalcis, Euboea.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Nicomachus was said to have belonged to the medical guild of Asclepiadae and was likely responsible for Aristotle's early interest in biology and medicine.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Ancient tradition held that Aristotle's family descended from the legendary physician Asclepius and his son Machaon.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Both of Aristotle's parents died when he was still at a young age and Proxenus of Atarneus became his guardian.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Although little information about Aristotle's childhood has survived, he probably spent some time in the Macedonian capital Pella, making his first connections with the Macedonian monarchy.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] At the age of seventeen or eighteen, Aristotle moved to Athens to continue his education at Plato's Academy.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He became distinguished as a researcher and lecturer, earning for himself the nickname "mind of the school" by his tutor Plato.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In Athens, he probably experienced the Eleusinian Mysteries as he wrote when describing the sights one viewed at the Mysteries, "to experience is to learn" (παθεĩν μαθεĩν).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle remained in Athens for nearly twenty years before leaving in 348/47 BC after Plato's death.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The traditional story about his departure records that he was disappointed with the academy's direction after control passed to Plato's nephew Speusippus, although it is possible that the anti-Macedonian sentiments in Athens could have also influenced his decision.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle left with Xenocrates to Assos in Asia Minor, where he was invited by his former fellow student Hermias of Atarneus; he stayed there for a few years, leaving around the time of Hermias' death.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] While at Assos, Aristotle and his colleague Theophrastus did extensive research in botany and marine biology, which they later continued at the near-by island of Lesbos.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] During this time, Aristotle married Pythias, Hermias's adoptive daughter and niece, and had a daughter whom they also named Pythias.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In 343/42 BC, Aristotle was invited to Pella by Philip II of Macedon to become the tutor to his thirteen-year-old son Alexander; a choice perhaps influenced by the relationship of Aristotle's family with the Macedonian dynasty.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle taught Alexander at the private school of Mieza, in the gardens of the Nymphs, the royal estate near Pella.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Alexander's education probably included a number of subjects, such as ethics and politics, as well as standard literary texts, like Euripides and Homer.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] It is likely that during Aristotle's time in the Macedonian court, other prominent nobles, like Ptolemy and Cassander, would have occasionally attended his lectures.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle encouraged Alexander toward eastern conquest, and his own attitude towards Persia was strongly ethnocentric.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In one famous example, he counsels Alexander to be "a leader to the Greeks and a despot to the barbarians".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Alexander's education under the guardianship of Aristotle likely lasted for only a few years, as at around the age of sixteen he returned to Pella and was appointed regent of Macedon by his father Philip.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] During this time, Aristotle gifted Alexander an annotated copy of the *Iliad*, which is said to have become one of Alexander's most prized possessions.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Scholars speculate that two of Aristotle's now lost works, *On kingship* and *On behalf of the Colonies*, were composed by the philosopher for the young prince.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle returned to Athens for the second and final time a year after Philip II's assassination in 336 BC.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] As a metic, Aristotle could not own property in Athens and thus rented a building known as the Lyceum (named after the sacred grove of Apollo *Lykeios*), in which he established his own school.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The building included a gymnasium and a colonnade (*peripatos*), from which the school acquired the name *Peripatetic*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle conducted courses and research at the school for the next twelve years.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He often lectured small groups of distinguished students and, along with some of them, such as Theophrastus, Eudemus, and Aristoxenus, Aristotle built a large library which included manuscripts, maps, and museum objects.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] While in Athens, his wife Pythias died and Aristotle became involved with Herpyllis of Stagira.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] They had a son whom Aristotle named after his father, Nicomachus.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] This period in Athens, between 335 and 323 BC, is when Aristotle is believed to have composed many of his philosophical works.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He wrote many dialogues, of which only fragments have survived.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Those works that have survived are in treatise form and were not, for the most part, intended for widespread publication; they are generally thought to be lecture aids for his students.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] His most important treatises include *Physics*, *Metaphysics*, *Nicomachean Ethics*, *Politics*, *On the Soul* and *Poetics*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] A widespread speculation in antiquity suggested that Aristotle played a role in Alexander's death, but the only evidence of this is an unlikely claim made some six years after the death.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Following Alexander's death, anti-Macedonian sentiment in Athens was rekindled.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He died in Chalcis, Euboea of natural causes later that same year, having named his student Antipater as his chief executor and left a will in which he asked to be buried next to his wife.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle left his works to Theophrastus, his successor as the head of the Lyceum, who in turn passed them down to Neleus of Scepsis in Asia Minor.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] There, the papers remained hidden for protection until they were purchased by the collector Apellicon.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In the meantime, many copies of Aristotle's major works had already begun to circulate and be used in the Lyceum of Athens, Alexandria, and later in Rome.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] With the *Prior Analytics*, Aristotle is credited with the earliest systematic study of logic, and his conception of it was the dominant form of Western logic until 19th-century advances in mathematical logic.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Kant even stated in the *Critique of Pure Reason* that with Aristotle, logic reached its completion.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Most of Aristotle's work is probably not in its original form, because it was most likely edited by students and later lecturers.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The logical works of Aristotle were compiled into a set of six books called the *Organon* around 40 BC by Andronicus of Rhodes or others among his followers.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The order of the books (or the teachings from which they are composed) is not certain, but this list was derived from analysis of Aristotle's writings.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The first three treatises form the core of the logical theory *stricto sensu*: the grammar of the language of logic and the correct rules of reasoning.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The *Rhetoric* is not conventionally included, but it states that it relies on the *Topics*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] What is today called *Aristotelian logic* with its types of syllogism (methods of logical argument), Aristotle himself would have labelled "analytics".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The term "logic" he reserved to mean *dialectics*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's *Posterior Analytics* contains his account of demonstration, or demonstrative knowledge, what would today be considered the study of epistemology rather than logic, but which for Aristotle is deeply connected with his account of syllogism.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] For Aristotle, knowledge is that which is necessarily the case, along with the study of causes.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The word "metaphysics" comes from the title of a collection of works by Aristotle bearing that title.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] However, Aristotle did not use that term himself, which is due to a later compiler, but instead called it "first philosophy" or theology.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He distinguished this as "the study of being qua being" which, as opposed to other studies of being, such as mathematics and natural science, studies that which is eternal, unchanging, and immaterial.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle examines the concepts of substance (*ousia*) and essence (*to ti ên einai*, "the what it was to be") in his *Metaphysics* (Book VII), and he concludes that a particular substance is a combination of both matter and form, a philosophical theory called hylomorphism.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In Book VIII, he distinguishes the matter of the substance as the substratum, or the stuff of which it is composed.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] For example, the matter of a house is the bricks, stones, timbers, etc., or whatever constitutes the *potential* house, while the form of the substance is the *actual* house, namely 'covering for bodies and chattels' or any other differentia that let us define something as a house.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The formula that gives the components is the account of the matter, and the formula that gives the differentia is the account of the form.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Like his teacher Plato, Aristotle's philosophy aims at the universal.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's ontology has the universal (*katholou*) exist in a lesser sense than particulars (*kath' hekaston*), things in the world, whereas for Plato the universal is a realer, separately existing form which particular things merely imitate.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] For Aristotle, universals still exist, but are only encountered when "instantiated" in a particular substance.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In addition, Aristotle disagreed with Plato about the location of universals.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Where Plato spoke of the forms as existing separately from the things that participate in them, Aristotle maintained that universals are multiply located.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] So, according to Aristotle, the form of apple exists within each apple, rather than in the world of the forms.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] 3. alteration, which is change in quality.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Coming-to-be is a change where the substrate of the thing that has undergone the change has itself changed.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In that particular change he introduces the concept of potentiality (*dynamis*) and actuality (*entelecheia*) in association with the matter and the form.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Referring to potentiality, this is what a thing is capable of doing or being acted upon if the conditions are right and it is not prevented by something else.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] For example, the seed of a plant in the soil is potentially (*dynamei*) a plant, and if it is not prevented by something, it will become a plant.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Potentially, beings can either 'act' (*poiein*) or 'be acted upon' (*paschein*), which can be either innate or learned.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] For example, the eyes possess the potentiality of sight (innate – being acted upon), while the capability of playing the flute can be possessed by learning (exercise – acting).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Actuality is the fulfilment of the end of the potentiality.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Because the end (*telos*) is the principle of every change, and potentiality exists for the sake of the end, actuality, accordingly, is the end.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Referring then to the previous example, it can be said that an actuality is when a plant does one of the activities that plants do.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In summary, the matter used to make a house has potentiality to be a house and both the activity of building and the form of the final house are actualities, which is also a final cause or end.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Then Aristotle proceeds and concludes that the actuality is prior to potentiality in formula, in time and in substantiality.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] With this definition of the particular substance (i.e., matter and form), Aristotle tries to solve the problem of the unity of the beings, for example, "what is it that makes a man one"?
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Since, according to Plato there are two Ideas: animal and biped, how then is man a unity?
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] However, according to Aristotle, the potential being (matter) and the actual one (form) are one and the same.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's "natural philosophy" spans a wide range of natural phenomena including those now covered by physics, biology and other natural sciences.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In Aristotle's terminology, "natural philosophy" is a branch of philosophy examining the phenomena of the natural world, and includes fields that would be regarded today as physics, biology and other natural sciences.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's work encompassed virtually all facets of intellectual inquiry.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle makes philosophy in the broad sense coextensive with reasoning, which he also would describe as "science".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] However, his use of the term *science* carries a different meaning than that covered by the term "scientific method".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] For Aristotle, "all science (*dianoia*) is either practical, poetical or theoretical" (*Metaphysics* 1025b25).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] His practical science includes ethics and politics; his poetical science means the study of fine arts including poetry; his theoretical science covers physics, mathematics and metaphysics.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In his *On Generation and Corruption*, Aristotle related each of the four elements proposed earlier by Empedocles, earth, water, air, and fire, to two of the four sensible qualities, hot, cold, wet, and dry.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In the Empedoclean scheme, all matter was made of the four elements, in differing proportions.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's scheme added the heavenly aether, the divine substance of the heavenly spheres, stars and planets.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle describes two kinds of motion: "violent" or "unnatural motion", such as that of a thrown stone, in the *Physics* (254b10), and "natural motion", such as of a falling object, in *On the Heavens* (300a20).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In violent motion, as soon as the agent stops causing it, the motion stops also: in other words, the natural state of an object is to be at rest, since Aristotle does not address friction.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] With this understanding, it can be observed that, as Aristotle stated, heavy objects (on the ground, say) require more force to make them move; and objects pushed with greater force move faster.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Natural motion depends on the element concerned: the aether naturally moves in a circle around the heavens, while the 4 Empedoclean elements move vertically up (like fire, as is observed) or down (like earth) towards their natural resting places.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle implies that in a vacuum the speed of fall would become infinite, and concludes from this apparent absurdity that a vacuum is not possible.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Opinions have varied on whether Aristotle intended to state quantitative laws.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Henri Carteron held the "extreme view" that Aristotle's concept of force was basically qualitative, but other authors reject this.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Archimedes corrected Aristotle's theory that bodies move towards their natural resting places; metal boats can float if they displace enough water; floating depends in Archimedes' scheme on the mass and volume of the object, not, as Aristotle thought, its elementary composition.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's writings on motion remained influential until the early modern period.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] John Philoponus (in late antiquity) and Galileo (in the early modern period) are said to have shown by experiment that Aristotle's claim that a heavier object falls faster than a lighter object is incorrect.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] A contrary opinion is given by Carlo Rovelli, who argues that Aristotle's physics of motion is correct within its domain of validity, that of objects in the Earth's gravitational field immersed in a fluid such as air.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In this system, heavy bodies in steady fall indeed travel faster than light ones (whether friction is ignored, or not), and they do fall more slowly in a denser medium.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle was aware of Pythagorean optics.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He used optics in his *Meteorology*, treating it as a science.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He viewed optics as stating the laws of sight, thus combining what is now treated as physics and biology.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The process of seeing involved the movement of a visible form from the thing seen through the air (or other medium) to the eye, where the form comes to rest.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle does not analyse the nature of this movement; he does not anticipate geometrical optics.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] According to Aristotle, spontaneity and chance are causes of some things, distinguishable from other types of cause such as simple necessity.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Chance as an incidental cause lies in the realm of accidental things, "from what is spontaneous".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] There is also more a specific kind of chance, which Aristotle names "luck", that only applies to people's moral choices.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle was one of the first people to record any geological observations.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He stated that geological change was too slow to be observed in one person's lifetime.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle also made many observations about the hydrologic cycle.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle was the first person to study biology systematically, and biology forms a large part of his writings.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He spent two years observing and describing the zoology of Lesbos and the surrounding seas, including in particular the Pyrrha lagoon in the centre of Lesbos.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] His data in *History of Animals*, *Generation of Animals*, *Movement of Animals*, and *Parts of Animals* are from his own observations, statements by knowledgeable people such as beekeepers and fishermen, and accounts by travellers.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] His apparent emphasis on animals rather than plants is a historical accident: his works on botany have been lost, but two books on plants by his pupil Theophrastus have survived.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle reports on sea life from observation on Lesbos and the catches of fishermen.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He describes the catfish, electric ray, and frogfish, as well as cephalopods such as the octopus and paper nautilus.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] His description of the hectocotyl arm of cephalopods, used in sexual reproduction, was widely disbelieved until the 19th century.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He gives accurate descriptions of the four-chambered stomachs of ruminants, and of the ovoviviparous embryological development of the hound shark.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He notes that an animal's structure is well matched to function so the heron has a long neck, long legs, and a sharp spear-like beak, whereas ducks have short legs and webbed feet.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Darwin, too, noted such differences, but unlike Aristotle used the data to come to the theory of evolution.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's writings can seem to imply evolution, but Aristotle saw mutations or hybridizations as rare accidents, distinct from natural causes.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He was thus critical of Empedocles's theory of a "survival of the fittest" origin of living things and their organs, and ridiculed the idea that accidents could lead to orderly results.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In modern terms, he nowhere says that different species can have a common ancestor, that one kind can change into another, or that kinds can become extinct.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle did not do experiments in the modern sense.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He made observations, or at most investigative procedures like dissection.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In *Generation of Animals*, he opens a fertilized hen's egg to see the embryo's heart beating inside.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Instead, he systematically gathered data, discovering patterns common to whole groups of animals, and inferring possible causal explanations from these.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] This style is common in modern biology when large amounts of data become available in a new field, such as genomics.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] This sets out testable hypotheses and constructs a narrative explanation of what is observed.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In this sense, Aristotle's biology is scientific.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] From his data, Aristotle inferred rules relating the life-history features of live-bearing tetrapods (terrestrial placental mammals) that he studied.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He correctly predicted that brood size decreases with body mass; that lifespan increases with gestation period and with body mass; and that fecundity decreases with lifespan.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle distinguished about 500 animal species, arranging them in a nonreligious graded scale of perfection, with man at the top.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The highest gave live birth to hot and wet creatures, the lowest laid cold, dry mineral-like eggs.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He grouped what a zoologist would call vertebrates as "animals with blood", and invertebrates as "animals without blood".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Those with blood were divided into live-bearing (mammals), and egg-laying (birds, reptiles, fish).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Those without blood were insects, crustacea and hard-shelled molluscs.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He recognised that animals did not exactly fit onto a scale, and noted exceptions, such as that sharks had a placenta.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] To a biologist, the explanation is convergent evolution.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Philosophers of science have concluded that Aristotle was not interested in taxonomy, but zoologists think otherwise.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's psychology, in his treatise *On the Soul* (*peri psychēs*), posits three kinds of soul (*psyches*): the vegetative, sensitive, and rational.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The vegetative soul is concerned with growth and nourishment.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The sensitive soul experiences sensations and movement.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The uniquely human, rational soul receives forms of things and compares them using the *nous* (intellect) and *logos* (reason).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] For Aristotle, the soul is the form of a living being.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Because all beings are composites of form and matter, the form of living beings is that which endows them with what is specific to living beings, e.g., the ability to initiate movement.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In contrast to earlier philosophers, but in accordance with the Egyptians, he placed the rational soul in the heart.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle distinguished sensation and thought, unlike previous philosophers except for Alcmaeon.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In *On the Soul*, Aristotle criticizes Plato's theory of the soul and develops his own in response.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Firstly he criticises Plato's *Timaeus* which holds the soul takes up space and can come into physical contact with bodies.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] 20th-century scholarship held that Aristotle had here misinterpreted Plato.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle also argued that Plato's view of reincarnation entails that a soul and its body can be mis-matched; in principle, Aristotle alleges, any soul can go with any body, according to Plato's theory.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] According to Aristotle in *On the Soul*, memory is the ability to hold a perceived experience in the mind and to distinguish between the internal "appearance" and a past occurrence.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] A memory is a mental picture (phantasm) that can be recovered.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] An impression is left on a semi-fluid bodily organ that undergoes changes in order to make a memory.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] A memory occurs when stimuli such as sights or sounds are so complex that the nervous system cannot receive them all at once.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] These changes are the same as those involved in sensation, 'common sense', and thinking.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle uses the term 'memory' for the actual retaining of an experience in the impression that develops from sensation, and for the intellectual anxiety that comes with the impression because it is formed at a particular time and processing specific contents.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Memory is of the past, prediction is of the future, and sensation is of the present.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Retrieval of impressions cannot be performed suddenly.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] A transitional channel is needed and located in past experiences, both for previous experience and present experience.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Because Aristotle believed people perceive all kinds of sense perceptions as impressions, people continually weave together new impressions of experiences.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] To search for impressions, people search memory itself.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Within memory, if an experience is offered instead of a specific memory, that person will reject this experience until they find what they are looking for.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Recollection occurs when a retrieved experience naturally follows another.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] If the chain of "images" is needed, one memory stimulates the next.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] When people recall experiences, they stimulate certain previous experiences until they reach the one that is needed.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Recollection is thus the self-directed activity of retrieving information stored in a memory impression.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Only humans can remember impressions of intellectual activity, such as numbers and words.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Animals that have perception of time can retrieve memories of their past observations.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Remembering involves only perception of the things remembered and of the time passed.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle believed the chain of thought that achieves recollection of impressions was connected systematically in relationships such as similarity, contrast, and contiguity, described in his laws of association.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle believed that past experiences are hidden within the mind.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] A force operates to awaken the hidden material to bring up the actual experience.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Association is the power innate in a mental state, which operates upon the unexpressed remains of former experiences, allowing them to be recalled.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle describes sleep in *On Sleep and Wakefulness*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] It is a result of overuse of the senses or of digestion, and is vital to the body.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] While a person is asleep, the critical activities, which include thinking, sensing, recalling and remembering, do not function.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Since a person cannot sense during sleep, they cannot have desire.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] However, the senses work during sleep, albeit differently.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Dreams do not involve sensing a stimulus.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Sensation is involved, but in an altered manner.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle explains that when a person stares at a moving stimulus such as the waves in a body of water, and then looks away, the next thing they look at appears to have a wavelike motion.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] When a person perceives a stimulus and it is no longer the focus of their attention, it leaves an impression.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] When the body is awake, a person constantly encounters new stimuli and so the impressions of previous stimuli are ignored.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] However, during sleep the impressions made throughout the day are noticed, free of distractions.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] So, dreams result from these lasting impressions.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Since impressions are all that are left, dreams do not resemble waking experience.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] During sleep, a person is in an altered state of mind, like a person who is overtaken by strong feelings.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] For example, a person who has a strong infatuation with someone may begin to think they see that person everywhere.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Since a person sleeping is in a suggestible state and unable to make judgements, they become easily deceived by what appears in their dreams, like the infatuated person.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] This leads them to believe the dream is real, even when the dreams are absurd.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In *De Anima* iii 3, Aristotle ascribes the ability to create, to store, and to recall images to the faculty of imagination, *phantasia*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] One component of Aristotle's theory disagrees with previously held beliefs.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He claimed that dreams are not foretelling and not sent by a divine being.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle reasoned that instances in which dreams resemble future events are simply coincidences.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Any sensory experience perceived while a person is asleep, such as actually hearing a door close, does not qualify as part of a dream.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Images of dreams must be a result of lasting impressions of waking sensory experiences.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's practical philosophy covers areas such as ethics, politics, economics, and rhetoric.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle was a virtue ethicist who considered ethics to be a practical rather than theoretical study, i.e., one aimed at becoming good and doing good rather than knowing for its own sake.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He wrote several treatises on ethics, most notably including the *Nicomachean Ethics*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle taught that virtue has to do with the proper function (*ergon*) of a thing.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] An eye is only a good eye in so much as it can see because the proper function of an eye is sight.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle reasoned that humans must have a function specific to humans, and that this function must be an activity of the *psuchē* (*soul*) in accordance with reason (*logos*).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle identified such an optimum activity (the virtuous mean, between the accompanying vices of excess or deficiency) of the soul as the aim of all human deliberate action, *eudaimonia*, generally translated as "happiness" or sometimes "well-being".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] To have the potential of ever being happy in this way necessarily requires a good character (*ēthikē* *aretē*), often translated as moral or ethical virtue or excellence.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] When the best people come to live life this way their practical wisdom (*phronesis*) and their intellect (*nous*) can develop with each other towards the highest possible human virtue, the wisdom of an accomplished theoretical or speculative thinker, or in other words, a philosopher.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In addition to his works on ethics, which address the individual, Aristotle addressed the city in his work titled *Politics*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle considered the city to be a natural community.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Moreover, he considered the city to be prior in importance to the family, which in turn is prior to the individual, "for the whole must of necessity be prior to the part".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He famously stated that "man is by nature a political animal" and argued that humanity's defining factor among others in the animal kingdom is its rationality.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle conceived of politics as being like an organism rather than like a machine, and as a collection of parts, none of which can exist without the others.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's conception of the city is organic, and he is considered one of the first to conceive of the city in this manner.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The common modern understanding of a political community as a modern state is quite different from Aristotle's understanding.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Although he was aware of the existence and potential of larger empires, the natural community according to Aristotle was the city (*polis*) which functions as a political "community" or "partnership" (*koinōnia*).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle made substantial contributions to economic thought, especially to thought in the Middle Ages.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In *Politics*, Aristotle addresses the city, property, and trade.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] His response to criticisms of private property, in Lionel Robbins's view, anticipated later proponents of private property among philosophers and economists, as it related to the overall utility of social arrangements.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle believed that although communal arrangements may seem beneficial to society, and that although private property is often blamed for social strife, such evils in fact come from human nature.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] In *Politics*, Aristotle offers one of the earliest accounts of the origin of money.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Money came into use because people became dependent on one another, importing what they needed and exporting the surplus.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] For the sake of convenience, people then agreed to deal in something that is intrinsically useful and easily applicable, such as iron or silver.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's discussions on retail and interest was a major influence on economic thought in the Middle Ages.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He had a low opinion of retail, believing that contrary to using money to procure things one needs in managing the household, retail trade seeks to make a profit.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] It thus uses goods as a means to an end, rather than as an end unto itself.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He believed that retail trade was in this way unnatural.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Similarly, Aristotle considered making a profit through interest unnatural, as it makes a gain out of the money itself, and not from its use.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle gave a summary of the function of money that was perhaps remarkably precocious for his time.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He wrote that because it is impossible to determine the value of every good through a count of the number of other goods it is worth, the necessity arises of a single universal standard of measurement.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Money thus allows for the association of different goods and makes them "commensurable".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He goes on to state that money is also useful for future exchange, making it a sort of security.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] That is, "if we do not want a thing now, we shall be able to get it when we do want it".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle's *Rhetoric* proposes that a speaker can use three basic kinds of appeals to persuade his audience: *ethos* (an appeal to the speaker's character), *pathos* (an appeal to the audience's emotion), and *logos* (an appeal to logical reasoning).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He also categorizes rhetoric into three genres: epideictic (ceremonial speeches dealing with praise or blame), forensic (judicial speeches over guilt or innocence), and deliberative (speeches calling on an audience to decide on an issue).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle also outlines two kinds of rhetorical proofs: *enthymeme* (proof by syllogism) and *paradeigma* (proof by example).
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle writes in his *Poetics* that epic poetry, tragedy, comedy, dithyrambic poetry, painting, sculpture, music, and dance are all fundamentally acts of *mimesis* ("imitation"), each varying in imitation by medium, object, and manner.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He applies the term *mimesis* both as a property of a work of art and also as the product of the artist's intention and contends that the audience's realisation of the *mimesis* is vital to understanding the work itself.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle states that *mimesis* is a natural instinct of humanity that separates humans from animals and that all human artistry "follows the pattern of nature".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The forms also differ in their object of imitation.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Comedy, for instance, is a dramatic imitation of men worse than average; whereas tragedy imitates men slightly better than average.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Lastly, the forms differ in their manner of imitation – through narrative or character, through change or no change, and through drama or no drama.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] While it is believed that Aristotle's *Poetics* originally comprised two books – one on comedy and one on tragedy – only the portion that focuses on tragedy has survived.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle taught that tragedy is composed of six elements: plot-structure, character, style, thought, spectacle, and lyric poetry.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] The characters in a tragedy are merely a means of driving the story; and the plot, not the characters, is the chief focus of tragedy.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Tragedy is the imitation of action arousing pity and fear, and is meant to effect the catharsis of those same emotions.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle concludes *Poetics* with a discussion on which, if either, is superior: epic or tragic mimesis.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] He suggests that because tragedy possesses all the attributes of an epic, possibly possesses additional attributes such as spectacle and music, is more unified, and achieves the aim of its mimesis in shorter scope, it can be considered superior to epic.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p01] Aristotle was a keen systematic collector of riddles, folklore, and proverbs; he and his school had a special interest in the riddles of the Delphic Oracle and studied the fables of Aesop.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] More than 2300 years after his death, Aristotle remains one of the most influential people who ever lived.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] He contributed to almost every field of human knowledge then in existence, and was the founder of many new fields.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] According to the philosopher Bryan Magee, "it is doubtful whether any human being has ever known as much as he did".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Aristotle has been regarded as the first scientist.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Aristotle was the founder of term logic, pioneered the study of zoology, and benefited future scientists and philosophers through his contributions to the scientific method.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Taneli Kukkonen, observes that his achievement in founding two sciences is unmatched, and his reach in influencing "every branch of intellectual enterprise" including Western ethical and political theory, theology, rhetoric, and literary analysis is equally long.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Aristotle has been called the father of logic, biology, political science, zoology, embryology, natural law, scientific method, rhetoric, psychology, realism, criticism, individualism, teleology, and meteorology.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] What follows is an overview of the transmission and influence of his texts and ideas into the modern era.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] The immediate influence of Aristotle's work was felt as the Lyceum grew into the Peripatetic school.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Aristotle's students included Aristoxenus, Dicaearchus, Demetrius of Phalerum, Eudemos of Rhodes, Harpalus, Hephaestion, Mnason of Phocis, Nicomachus, and Theophrastus.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Aristotle's pupil and successor, Theophrastus, wrote the *History of Plants*, a pioneering work in botany.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Some of his technical terms remain in use, such as carpel from *carpos*, fruit, and pericarp, from *pericarpion*, seed chamber.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Theophrastus was much less concerned with formal causes than Aristotle was, instead pragmatically describing how plants functioned.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Under the Ptolemies, the first medical teacher at Alexandria, Herophilus of Chalcedon, corrected Aristotle, placing intelligence in the brain, and connected the nervous system to motion and sensation.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Herophilus also distinguished between veins and arteries, noting that the latter pulse while the former do not.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] In antiquity, Aristotle's writings were divisible into two groups; the "exoteric" works, intended for the public, and the "esoteric" treatises, for use within the Lyceum school.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] The primary way that ancient philosophers in the Roman empire engaged with Aristotle's technical work was via philosophical commentary; interpretation and explication of the text of Aristotle along with their own synthesis and views on the topics discussed by Aristotle.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] In the 3rd century, Neoplatonism emerged as the dominant philosophical school.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] This study program began with the *Categories*, which the Neoplatonist philosopher Porphyry of Tyre wrote an introduction to, called *Isagoge*, which went on to influence subsequent philosophy in late antiquity and the medieval period.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] With the rise of Christianity and closure of the pagan schools by the order of Justinian in 529, the study of Aristotle and other philosophers in the remainder of the Byzantine period was primarily from a Christian perspective.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] John Philoponus stands out for having attempted a fundamental critique of Aristotle's views on the eternity of the world, movement, and other elements of Aristotelian thought.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Philoponus questioned Aristotle's teaching of physics, noting its flaws and introducing the theory of impetus to explain his observations.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] After a hiatus of several centuries, formal commentary by Eustratius and Michael of Ephesus reappeared in the late eleventh and early twelfth centuries, apparently sponsored by Anna Comnena.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Michael of Ephesus wrote commentaries on the works of Aristotle's animal biology and the *Politics*, completing the series of commentaries on Aristotle's extant works.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Aristotle's works underwent a revival in the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Translated into Arabic, Aristotle's logic, ethics, and natural philosophy inspired early Islamic scholars.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Aristotle is considered the most influential figure in the history of Arabic philosophy and was revered in early Islamic theology.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Most surviving works of Aristotle, as well as some of the original Greek commentaries, were translated into Arabic and studied by Muslim philosophers, scientists, and scholars.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Through commentaries and critical engagements, figures like Al-Kindi, Al-Farabi, Ibn Sina (Avicenna), and Averroes breathed new life into Aristotle's ideas.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] They harmonized his logic with Islamic theology, employed his scientific methodology to explore the natural world, and reinterpreted his ethics within the framework of Islamic morality.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Islamic thinkers embraced Aristotle's rigorous methods while challenging his conclusions where they diverged from their religious beliefs, which later influenced Thomas Aquinas and other Western Christian scholastic philosophers.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Medieval Muslim scholars described Aristotle as the "First Teacher".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] The title was later used by Western philosophers (as in Dante's poem) who were influenced by the tradition of Islamic philosophy.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Moses Maimonides (considered to be the foremost intellectual figure of medieval Judaism) adopted Aristotelianism from the Islamic scholars and based his *Guide for the Perplexed* on it; the work became the basis of Jewish scholastic philosophy.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Maimonides also considered Aristotle to be the greatest philosopher that ever lived, and styled him as the "chief of the philosophers".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Also, in his letter to Samuel ibn Tibbon, Maimonides observes that there is no need for Samuel to study the writings of philosophers who preceded Aristotle because the works of the latter are "sufficient by themselves and [superior] to all that were written before them.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] His intellect, Aristotle's is the extreme limit of human intellect, apart from him upon whom the divine emanation has flowed forth to such an extent that they reach the level of prophecy, there being no level higher".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] With the loss of the study of ancient Greek in the early medieval Latin West, Aristotle was practically unknown there from c.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] 1100 except through the Latin translation of the *Organon* made by Boethius.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] In the twelfth and thirteenth centuries, interest in Aristotle revived and Latin Christians had translations made, both from Arabic translations, such as those by Gerard of Cremona, and from the original Greek, such as those by James of Venice and William of Moerbeke.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] These thinkers blended Aristotelian philosophy with Christianity, bringing the thought of Ancient Greece into the Middle Ages.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Scholars such as Boethius, Peter Abelard, and John Buridan worked on Aristotelian logic.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] According to scholar Roger Theodore Lafferty, Dante built up the philosophy of the *Comedy* on a foundation of Aristotle, just as the scholastics used Aristotle as the basis for their thinking.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Dante knew Aristotle directly from Latin translations of his works and indirectly through quotations in the works of Albert Magnus.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Dante acknowledges Aristotle's influence explicitly in the poem, when Virgil justifies the Inferno's structure by citing the *Nicomachean Ethics*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Dante refers to him as "he / Who is acknowledged Master of those who know".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] In the early modern period, scientists such as William Harvey in England and Galileo Galilei in Italy reacted against the theories of Aristotle and other classical era thinkers like Galen, establishing new theories based to some degree on observation and experiment.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Harvey demonstrated the circulation of the blood, establishing that the heart functioned as a pump rather than being the seat of the soul and the controller of the body's heat, as Aristotle thought.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Galileo used more doubtful arguments to displace Aristotle's physics, proposing that bodies all fall at the same speed whatever their weight.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] The English mathematician George Boole fully accepted Aristotle's logic, but decided "to go under, over, and beyond" it with his system of algebraic logic in his 1854 book *The Laws of Thought*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] This gives logic a mathematical foundation with equations, enables it to solve equations as well as check validity, and allows it to handle a wider class of problems by expanding propositions of any number of terms, not just two.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Charles Darwin regarded Aristotle as the most important contributor to the subject of biology.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] In an 1882 letter he wrote that "Linnaeus and Cuvier have been my two gods, though in very different ways, but they were mere schoolboys to old Aristotle".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Also, in later editions of the book "On the Origin of Species', Darwin traced evolutionary ideas as far back as Aristotle; the text he cites is a summary by Aristotle of the ideas of the earlier Greek philosopher Empedocles.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] The philosopher Bertrand Russell claimed that "almost every serious intellectual advance has had to begin with an attack on some Aristotelian doctrine".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Russell called Aristotle's ethics "repulsive", and labelled his logic "as definitely antiquated as Ptolemaic astronomy".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Russell stated that these errors make it difficult to do historical justice to Aristotle, until one remembers what an advance he made upon all of his predecessors.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] The Dutch historian of science Eduard Jan Dijksterhuis writes that Aristotle and his predecessors showed the difficulty of science by "proceed[ing] so readily to frame a theory of such a general character" on limited evidence from their senses.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] In 1985, the biologist Peter Medawar could still state in "pure seventeenth century" tones that Aristotle had assembled "a strange and generally speaking rather tiresome farrago of hearsay, imperfect observation, wishful thinking and credulity amounting to downright gullibility".
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Zoologists have frequently mocked Aristotle for errors and unverified secondhand reports.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] However, modern observation has confirmed several of his more surprising claims.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Aristotle's work remains largely unknown to modern scientists, though zoologists sometimes mention him as the father of biology or in particular of marine biology.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Practising zoologists are unlikely to adhere to Aristotle's chain of being, but its influence is still perceptible in the use of the terms "lower" and "upper" to designate taxa such as groups of plants.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] The evolutionary biologist Armand Marie Leroi has reconstructed Aristotle's biology, while Niko Tinbergen's four questions, based on Aristotle's four causes, are used to analyse animal behaviour; they examine function, phylogeny, mechanism, and ontogeny.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] The concept of homology began with Aristotle; the evolutionary developmental biologist Lewis I.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Held commented that he would be interested in the concept of deep homology.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] In systematics too, recent studies consider that Aristotle made important contributions to taxonomy and biological nomenclature.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Aristotle has been depicted by major artists including Lucas Cranach the Elder, Justus van Gent, Raphael, Paolo Veronese, Jusepe de Ribera, Rembrandt, and Francesco Hayez over the centuries.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Among the best-known depictions is Raphael's fresco *The School of Athens*, in the Vatican's Apostolic Palace, where the figures of Plato and Aristotle are central to the image, at the architectural vanishing point, reflecting their importance.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] The Aristotle Mountains in Antarctica are named after Aristotle.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] He was the first person known to conjecture, in his book *Meteorology*, the existence of a landmass in the southern high-latitude region, which he called *Antarctica*.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] Aristoteles is a crater on the Moon bearing the classical form of Aristotle's name.
[src:mpemba-effect/aristotle-p02] (6123) Aristoteles, an asteroid in the main asteroid belt, also bears the classical form of his name.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] In particle physics, a **baryon** is a type of composite subatomic particle that contains an odd number of valence quarks, conventionally three.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Protons and neutrons are examples of baryons; because baryons are composed of quarks, they belong to the hadron family of particles.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Baryons are also classified as fermions because they have half-integer spin.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The name "baryon", introduced by Abraham Pais, comes from the Greek word for "heavy" (βαρύς, *barýs*), because, at the time of their naming, most known elementary particles had lower masses than the baryons.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Each baryon has a corresponding antiparticle (antibaryon) where their corresponding antiquarks replace quarks.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] For example, a proton is made of two up quarks and one down quark; and its corresponding antiparticle, the antiproton, is made of two up antiquarks and one down antiquark.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Baryons participate in the residual strong force, which is mediated by particles known as mesons.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The most familiar baryons are protons and neutrons.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] These particles make up most of the mass of the visible matter in the universe and compose the nucleus of every atom (electrons, the other major component of the atom, are members of a different family of particles called leptons; leptons do not interact via the strong force).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Exotic baryons containing five quarks, called pentaquarks, have also been discovered and studied.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] A census of the Universe's baryons indicates that 10% of them could be found inside galaxies, 50% to 60% in the circumgalactic medium, and the remaining 30% to 40% could be located in the warm–hot intergalactic medium (WHIM).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Baryons are strongly interacting fermions; that is, they are acted on by the strong nuclear force and are described by Fermi–Dirac statistics, which apply to all particles obeying the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] This is in contrast to the bosons, which do not obey the exclusion principle.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Baryons, alongside mesons, are hadrons, composite particles composed of quarks.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Quarks have baryon numbers of *B* = ⁠1/3⁠ and antiquarks have baryon numbers of *B* = −⁠1/3⁠.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The term "baryon" usually refers to *triquarks*—baryons made of three quarks (*B* = ⁠1/3⁠ + ⁠1/3⁠ + ⁠1/3⁠ = 1).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Other exotic baryons have been proposed, such as pentaquarks—baryons made of four quarks and one antiquark (*B* = ⁠1/3⁠ + ⁠1/3⁠ + ⁠1/3⁠ + ⁠1/3⁠ − ⁠1/3⁠ = 1), but their existence is not generally accepted.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The particle physics community as a whole did not view their existence as likely in 2006, and in 2008, considered evidence to be overwhelmingly against the existence of the reported pentaquarks.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] However, in July 2015, the LHCb experiment observed two resonances consistent with pentaquark states in the Λ0 b → J/ψK− p decay, with a combined statistical significance of 15σ.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] In theory, heptaquarks (5 quarks, 2 antiquarks), nonaquarks (6 quarks, 3 antiquarks), etc. could also exist.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Nearly all matter that may be encountered or experienced in everyday life is baryonic matter, which includes atoms of any sort, and provides them with the property of mass.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Non-baryonic matter, as implied by the name, is any sort of matter that is not composed primarily of baryons.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] This might include neutrinos and free electrons, dark matter, supersymmetric particles, axions, and black holes.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The very existence of baryons is also a significant issue in cosmology because it is assumed that the Big Bang produced a state with equal amounts of baryons and antibaryons.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The process by which baryons came to outnumber their antiparticles is called baryogenesis.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Experiments are consistent with the number of quarks in the universe being conserved alongside the total baryon number, with antibaryons being counted as negative quantities.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Within the prevailing Standard Model of particle physics, the number of baryons may change in multiples of three due to the action of sphalerons, although this is rare and has not been observed under experiment.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Some Grand Unified Theories of particle physics also predict that a single proton can decay, changing the baryon number by one; however, this has not yet been observed under experiment.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The excess of baryons over antibaryons in the present universe is thought to be due to non-conservation of baryon number in the very early universe, though this is not well understood.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The concept of isospin was first proposed by Werner Heisenberg in 1932 to explain the similarities between protons and neutrons under the strong interaction.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Although they had different electric charges, their masses were so similar that physicists believed they were the same particle.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The different electric charges were explained as being the result of some unknown excitation similar to spin.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] This unknown excitation was later dubbed *isospin* by Eugene Wigner in 1937.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] This belief lasted until Murray Gell-Mann proposed the quark model in 1964 (containing originally only the u, d, and s quarks).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The success of the isospin model is now understood to be the result of the similar masses of u and d quarks.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Since u and d quarks have similar masses, particles made of the same number then also have similar masses.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The exact specific u and d quark composition determines the charge, as u quarks carry charge +⁠2/3⁠ while d quarks carry charge −⁠1/3⁠.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] For example, the four Deltas all have different charges (Δ++ (uuu), Δ+ (uud), Δ0 (udd), Δ− (ddd)), but have similar masses (~1,232 MeV/*c*2) as they are each made of a combination of three u or d quarks.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Under the isospin model, they were considered to be a single particle in different charged states.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The mathematics of isospin was modeled after that of spin.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Isospin projections varied in increments of 1 just like those of spin, and to each projection was associated a "charged state".
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Since the "Delta particle" had four "charged states", it was said to be of isospin *I* = ⁠3/2⁠.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Another example is the "nucleon particle".
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] As there were two nucleon "charged states", it was said to be of isospin ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The positive nucleon N+ (proton) was identified with *I*3 = +⁠1/2⁠ and the neutral nucleon N0 (neutron) with *I*3 = −⁠1/2⁠.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] where the *n* is the number of up and down quarks and antiquarks.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] In the "isospin picture", the four Deltas and the two nucleons were thought to be the different states of two particles.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] However, in the quark model, Deltas are different states of nucleons (the N++ or N− are forbidden by Pauli's exclusion principle).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Isospin, although conveying an inaccurate picture of things, is still used to classify baryons, leading to unnatural and often confusing nomenclature.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The strangeness flavour quantum number *S* (not to be confused with spin) was noticed to go up and down along with particle mass.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The higher the mass, the lower the strangeness (the more s quarks).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Particles could be described with isospin projections (related to charge) and strangeness (mass) (see the uds octet and decuplet figures on the right).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] As other quarks were discovered, new quantum numbers were made to have similar description of udc and udb octets and decuplets.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] If the quarks all had the same mass, their behaviour would be called *symmetric*, as they would all behave in the same way to the strong interaction.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Since quarks do not have the same mass, they do not interact in the same way (exactly like an electron placed in an electric field will accelerate more than a proton placed in the same field because of its lighter mass), and the symmetry is said to be broken.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] where *S*, *C*, *B*′, and *T* represent the strangeness, charm, bottomness and topness flavour quantum numbers, respectively.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Spin (quantum number *S*) is a vector quantity that represents the "intrinsic" angular momentum of a particle.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] It comes in increments of ⁠1/2⁠ *ħ* (pronounced "h-bar").
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The *ħ* is often dropped because it is the "fundamental" unit of spin, and it is implied that "spin 1" means "spin 1 *ħ*".
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] In some systems of natural units, *ħ* is chosen to be 1, and therefore does not appear anywhere.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Quarks are fermionic particles of spin ⁠1/2⁠ (*S* = ⁠1/2⁠).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Because spin projections vary in increments of 1 (that is, 1 *ħ*), a single quark has a spin vector of length ⁠1/2⁠, and has two spin projections (*S*z = +⁠1/2⁠ and *S*z = −⁠1/2⁠).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Two quarks can have their spins aligned, in which case the two spin vectors add to make a vector of length *S* = 1 and three spin projections (*S*z = +1, *S*z = 0, and *S*z = −1).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] If two quarks have unaligned spins, the spin vectors add up to make a vector of length *S* = 0 and has only one spin projection (*S*z = 0), etc.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Since baryons are made of three quarks, their spin vectors can add to make a vector of length *S* = ⁠3/2⁠, which has four spin projections (*S*z = +⁠3/2⁠, *S*z = +⁠1/2⁠, *S*z = −⁠1/2⁠, and *S*z = −⁠3/2⁠), or a vector of length *S* = ⁠1/2⁠ with two spin projections (*S*z = +⁠1/2⁠, and *S*z = −⁠1/2⁠).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] There is another quantity of angular momentum, called the orbital angular momentum (azimuthal quantum number L), that comes in increments of 1 *ħ*, which represent the angular moment due to quarks orbiting around each other.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The total angular momentum (total angular momentum quantum number *J*) of a particle is therefore the combination of intrinsic angular momentum (spin) and orbital angular momentum.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] It can take any value from *J* = |*L* − *S*| to *J* = |*L* + *S*|, in increments of 1.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Particle physicists are most interested in baryons with no orbital angular momentum (*L* = 0), as they correspond to ground states—states of minimal energy.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Therefore, the two groups of baryons most studied are the *S* = ⁠1/2⁠; *L* = 0 and *S* = ⁠3/2⁠; *L* = 0, which corresponds to *J* = ⁠1/2⁠+ and *J* = ⁠3/2⁠+, respectively, although they are not the only ones.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] This phenomenon of having multiple particles in the same total angular momentum configuration is called *degeneracy*.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] How to distinguish between these degenerate baryons is an active area of research in baryon spectroscopy.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] If the universe were reflected in a mirror, most of the laws of physics would be identical—things would behave the same way regardless of what we call "left" and what we call "right".
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] This concept of mirror reflection is called "intrinsic parity" or simply "parity" (*P*).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Gravity, the electromagnetic force, and the strong interaction all behave in the same way regardless of whether or not the universe is reflected in a mirror, and thus are said to conserve parity (P-symmetry).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] However, the weak interaction does distinguish "left" from "right", a phenomenon called parity violation (P-violation).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Based on this, if the wavefunction for each particle (in more precise terms, the quantum field for each particle type) were simultaneously mirror-reversed, then the new set of wavefunctions would perfectly satisfy the laws of physics (apart from the weak interaction).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] It turns out that this is not quite true: for the equations to be satisfied, the wavefunctions of certain types of particles have to be multiplied by −1, in addition to being mirror-reversed.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Such particle types are said to have negative or odd parity (*P* = −1, or alternatively *P* = –), while the other particles are said to have positive or even parity (*P* = +1, or alternatively *P* = +).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] As a consequence, baryons with no orbital angular momentum (*L* = 0) all have even parity (*P* = +).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Baryons are classified into groups according to their isospin (*I*) values and quark (*q*) content.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] There are six groups of baryons: nucleon (N), Delta (Δ), Lambda (Λ), Sigma (Σ), Xi (Ξ), and Omega (Ω).
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The rules for classification are defined by the Particle Data Group.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] These rules consider the up (u), down (d) and strange (s) quarks to be *light* and the charm (c), bottom (b), and top (t) quarks to be *heavy*.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The rules cover all the particles that can be made from three of each of the six quarks, even though baryons made of top quarks are not expected to exist because of the top quark's short lifetime.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] It is also a widespread (but not universal) practice to follow some additional rules when distinguishing between some states that would otherwise have the same symbol.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] Quarks carry a charge, so knowing the charge of a particle indirectly gives the quark content.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] For example, the rules above say that a Λ+ c contains a c quark and some combination of two u and/or d quarks.
[src:mpemba-effect/baryonic-matter] The c quark has a charge of (*Q* = +⁠2/3⁠), therefore the other two must be a u quark (*Q* = +⁠2/3⁠), and a d quark (*Q* = −⁠1/3⁠) to have the correct total charge (*Q* = +1).
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] The **Mpemba effect** is the observation that very hot liquids or colloids (such as ice cream) can freeze more quickly than colder ones, for similar volumes and surrounding conditions.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Physicists remain divided on the effect's reproducibility, precise definition, and underlying mechanisms.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] It is named after Erasto Mpemba, a Tanzanian teenager who studied it scientifically in the 1960s for the first time, along with Denis Osborne.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] The Mpemba effect was initially observed in only ice cream and water, and later in other colloids.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] It has been studied extensively in water, with mixed results, and some experiments finding no reproducible effect.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] It has also been studied in magnetic alloys, nanomechanical systems, and quantum systems.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] The definition of the Mpemba effect used in theoretical studies varies, making it difficult to compare experiments.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] A generalized definition is "*When a hotter system equilibrates faster than a colder one when both are quenched to the same low temperature.*" In water, this would be when the liquid has completely frozen.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] The effect is named after Tanzanian student Erasto Mpemba, who described it in 1963 in Form 3 of Magamba Secondary School, Tanganyika; when freezing a hot ice cream mixture in a cookery class, he noticed that it froze before a cold mixture.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] He later became a student at Mkwawa Secondary (formerly High) School in Iringa.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Denis Osborne from the University College in Dar es Salaam to give a lecture on physics.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] After the lecture, Mpemba asked him, "If you take two similar containers with equal volumes of water, one at 35 °C (95 °F) and the other at 100 °C (212 °F), and put them into a freezer, the one that started at 100 °C (212 °F) freezes first.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Why?" Osborne thought the student was mistaken at first, but, intrigued by the question, he experimented on the issue back at his workplace, and was amused to see he was able to confirm Mpemba's finding.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Osborne and Mpemba later published the results together in 1969, while Mpemba was studying at the College of African Wildlife Management.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Mpemba and Osborne described placing 70 ml (2.5 imp fl oz; 2.4 US fl oz) samples of water in 100 ml (3.5 imp fl oz; 3.4 US fl oz) beakers in the icebox of a domestic refrigerator on a sheet of polystyrene foam.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] They showed the time for freezing to start was longest with an initial temperature of 25 °C (77 °F) and that it was much less at around 90 °C (194 °F).
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] They ruled out loss of liquid volume by evaporation and the effect of dissolved air as significant factors.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In their setup, most heat loss was found to be from the liquid surface.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Various effects of heat on the freezing of water were described by ancient scientists, including Aristotle: "The fact that the water has previously been warmed contributes to its freezing quickly: for so it cools sooner.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Scottish scientist Joseph Black in 1775 investigated a special case of the phenomenon by comparing previously boiled with unboiled water.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] He found that the previously boiled water froze more quickly, even when evaporation was controlled for.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] He discussed the influence of stirring on the results of the experiment, noting that stirring the unboiled water led to it freezing at the same time as the previously boiled water, and also noted that stirring the very cold unboiled water led to immediate freezing.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Joseph Black then discussed Daniel Gabriel Fahrenheit's description of supercooling of water, arguing that the previously boiled water could not be as readily supercooled.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Modern studies using freezers with well-understood properties have observed the Mpemba effect where water supercools before freezing.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Water that starts out cooler tends to reach a lower supercooled temperature before freezing.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Some studies measure the time it takes for a sample to begin to freeze (the start of recalescence, the moment where the heat of freezing first starts to be released) the time it takes to completely freeze, or the difference: the time from the onset of recalescence to the completion of freezing.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Some also measure the time it takes for a sample to reach the freezing point of the fluid, before any freezing has begun.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In 1995, David Auerbach studied glass beakers placed into a liquid cooling bath, where the water supercooled to −6 to −18 °C (21 to 0 °F; 267 to 255 K) before freezing.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In some cases water which started off hotter began freezing first.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Considerable random variation was observed in the time required for spontaneous freezing to start, and Auerbach observed the Mpemba effect more frequently when the ambient temperature was between −6 and −12 °C (21 and 10 °F).
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] James Brownridge later studied a variety of initial conditions and containers, measuring the time to the onset of recalescence, and found that while hot samples sometimes froze first this was also affected by properties of the container holding the liquid.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Writing for *New Scientist*, Mick O'Hare recommended starting the experiment with containers at 35 and 5 °C (95 and 41 °F; 308 and 278 K), respectively, to maximize the effect.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In 2021, John Bechhoefer described a way to reliably reproduce the effect.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In 2024, Argelia Ortega, et al. studied the freezing of small (1 to 20 mL or 0.03 to 0.7 US fl oz) drops in a Peltier cell with a thermographic camera, and found that hot drops consistently froze faster than cold ones, with a more pronounced difference for larger drops.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In particular, hot drops finished freezing sooner after the onset of recalescence, and experienced less of a temperature spike during the freezing process.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Some researchers have criticized studies of the Mpemba effect for not accounting for dissolved solids and gases, and other confounding factors.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Even among experiments that agree on a definition and observe the Mpemba effect for some experimental setups, they often do not observe it for all setups and starting conditions.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Ball described simple ways in which the effect might be observed, such as if a warmer temperature melts the frost on a cooling surface, thereby increasing thermal conductivity between the cooling surface and the water container.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In 2016, Burridge and Linden studied a slightly different measure, the time it took water samples to reach 0 °C but not freeze.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] They carried out their own experiments, and reviewed previous work by others.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] The original classroom observations of the Mpemba effect were of fresh ice cream, a colloid, freezing in a freezer.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] A generalized version of the Mpemba effect is "*when a hotter system equilibrates faster than a colder one when both are quenched to the same low temperature*." This has been modeled theoretically for simple systems such as single particles under Brownian motion.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] The possibility of a "strong Mpemba effect" where exponentially faster cooling can occur in a system at particular initial temperatures was predicted in 2019 by Klich, Raz, Hirschberg and Vucelja.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] If they existed, the effect in such systems would be easy to observe experimentally.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In 2020 the strong Mpemba effect was demonstrated experimentally by Avinash Kumar and John Boechhoefer in a single-particle colloidal system.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In 2022, that group also demonstrated an "inverse Mpemba effect" in a single-particle colloid where a cold system heats up much faster than a warmer one, under the right conditions.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Since 2020, quantum researchers have studied Mpemba effects in quantum systems as an example of how initial conditions of a system affects its thermal evolution.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In 2025, experimental observations by Zhang, et al. found a quantum strong Mpemba effect for a single trapped ion, and Chatterjee, et al. found the Mpemba effect occurs naturally during the cooling of nuclear spin states.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] While the definition of the Mpemba effect used in theoretical studies varies, several explanations have been offered for its occurrence.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In 2017, two research groups independently and simultaneously found a theoretical Mpemba effect and also predicted a new "inverse" Mpemba effect in which heating a cooled, far-from-equilibrium system takes less time than another system that is initially closer to equilibrium.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Zhiyue Lu and Oren Raz yielded a general criterion based on Markovian statistical mechanics, predicting the appearance of the inverse Mpemba effect in the Ising model and diffusion dynamics.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Antonio Lasanta and co-authors also predicted the direct and inverse Mpemba effects for a granular gas in a far-from-equilibrium initial state.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Lasanta's paper also suggested that a very generic mechanism leading to both Mpemba effects is due to a particle velocity distribution function that significantly deviates from the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In 2024, building on Kumar's work, Isha Malhotra simulated single colloids placed in a different, double-well potential, and predicted conditions under which two specific ranges of hotter starting temperatures lead to faster freezing, but not temperatures in between those ranges.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Supercooling is a component of many theoretical explanations, particularly the tendency of hot liquids that are cooled rapidly to start freezing at a higher supercool temperature.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Several molecular dynamics simulations have also supported that changes in hydrogen bonding during supercooling play a role in the process.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] In 2017, Yunwen Tao and co-authors suggested that the vast diversity and peculiar occurrence of different hydrogen bonds could contribute to the effect.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] They argued that the number of strong hydrogen bonds increases as temperature is elevated, and that the existence of the small strongly bonded clusters facilitates in turn the nucleation of hexagonal ice when warm water is rapidly cooled down.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] The authors used vibrational spectroscopy and modelling with density functional theory-optimized water clusters.
[src:mpemba-effect/mpemba-effect] Finkelstein state that there is a great variability in freezing speed, explaining the Mpemba effect as of stochastic origin.
